article.description: Greg Brunner scored 23 points and Iowa (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP)  held off a late rally to beat Northern Iowa 76-73 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Iowa's won 20 straight at home vs. Panthers
article.linkText: No. 24 Iowa holds off hard-charging No. Iowa
article.story: IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- All Greg Brunner needed was a little nudge from coach Steve Alford at halftime. Brunner responded in the second half, scoring 12 points in a 3:22 span to help Iowa (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) build what seemed to be a commanding 13-point lead. Brunner finished with 23 points, but the Hawkeyes sputtered down the stretch Tuesday night. They struggled to beat Northern Iowa, which lost 76-73 despite 25 points from Ben Jacobson. "Coach got into me because I was playing horrible defense and I think that kind of motivated me," said Brunner, who also had four rebounds and two assists. "I just think the whole team atmosphere picked up and we played really well together. I wanted to win this one bad." Iowa led by as much as 66-53 with 9:27 to go, but Brunner's hopes and hard work were nearly dashed in the final minutes. After Doug Thomas' tip-in with 7:24 left gave the Hawkeyes (7-1) a 68-56 lead, Northern Iowa stormed back. The Panthers' leading scorer, Erik Crawford, held in check most of the game, hit the first of three 3-pointers to put Northern Iowa (3-2) back on track. The Hawkeyes also struggled offensively down the stretch, making just two baskets and missing several free throws in the final six minutes. Crawford, who finished with nine points, hit his second 3 to bring the Panthers within six points, then nailed another deep from the left wing with 34 seconds left to make it 74-73. After Iowa's Adam Haluska missed a free throw, the Panthers had a chance to take the lead. But Jacobson, who had 25 points, missed a 15-footer with six seconds left. Jeff Horner grabbed the rebound, was fouled and hit both free throws to give the Hawkeyes their final margin of victory. Chris Foster's desperation shot, launched near midcourt just missed, sealing Iowa's 20th straight home victory over the Panthers. "I'm proud of my team from the standpoint that we battled back," Panther coach Greg McDermott said. "There's not an ounce of quit in that group." Horner added 16 points, including four 3-pointers. Erek Hansen and Pierre Pierce had 14 points apiece to propel Iowa to its fourth straight win. But it was Jacobson who had the game's hottest hand. He hit 10 of 16 shots, including 3-of-4 from 3-point range and accounted for nine of his team's first 13 points. He had a chance to give the Panthers the lead with six seconds left. After taking the pass on the left wing, Jacobson pulled up, fired over the Pierce's outstretched hand, but the ball rattled off the rim. "We had to put it in Jacobson's hands and let him win or lose the game for us," McDermott said. "He got us there. Pierre (Pierce) defended it well so we came up a little short." The Panthers also got 16 points and 11 rebounds from freshman center Eric Coleman. Grant Stout added 15 points and seven rebounds. The victory helped the Hawkeyes avenge last season's loss at Northern Iowa, one of several tough defeats that kept the Hawkeyes from earning an invitation to the NCAA tournament. Before the game, Horner expressed frustration about that loss and vowed to play better in the rematch. Horner responded on both ends of the floor, helping keep Crawford in check, grabbing nine rebounds and nailing two free throws after rebounding Jacobson's late miss. But it was Iowa's lapses on defense down the stretch that was most troubling to Alford. "We've got a long way to go defensively, but we're making some small steps in the right direction," he said. Both teams shot well, each finishing at 52.6 percent. But the Hawkeyes made 55 percent from 3-point range compared to 40 percent for Northern Iowa.
